                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18631214-136-offence-1 t18631214-name-133"></join>Emily Clough</persName>, she being under the age of sixteen, and unmarried.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COLLINS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LEWIS</hi>, <hi rend="italic">for the Defence, con<lb></lb>tended, first, that as the prisoner had only consented to receive the girl when she sought admittance to his room, that would not amount to taking her out of her mothers possession; secondly, that in the case of Reg.</hi> v. <hi rend="italic">Mantlelow it was held that the taking must be a permanent one, that is, with an intention permanently to deprive the parent of her possession; and in the case of Reg.</hi> v. <hi rend="italic">Downes (Sessions Papers</hi>, vol. li. p. 396), <hi rend="italic">which was reserved for the Court of Criminal Appeal, the Judges differing in opinion, the case had never been re-argued; thirdly, that in the case of Reg.</hi> v <hi rend="italic">Timms (See Sessions Papers</hi>, vol. lii. p. 600,) <hi rend="italic">the prisoner took the girl out of her parent's possession, she being a virgin, and slept with her two or three times, whereas in this case the girl was not a virgin, as she had had connexion with the prisoner twice before; that the case was the same as taking a handkerchief out of a person's pocket, which was not a felony unless done intending to deprive the owner of it permanently; and lastly, assuming the girl's statement to be untrue, and that she had previously slept with somebody else, she had reduced herself to a state in which there could be no taking her away.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">THE COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">considered that the case must go to the Jury.</hi>
               </p>
